!! Bulk MCP Tools (Reference)

The TiddlyWiki MCP server provides two ''bulk'' tools that operate on many tiddlers in one call:

|! Tool |! Purpose |
|`get_tiddlers` |Batch-read multiple tiddlers' fields and text in one MCP call |
|`replace_in_tiddlers` |Bulk find+replace across multiple tiddlers, with dry-run preview |

Both share three design principles: dry-run-or-cap-by-default (no surprise writes, no runaway output), filter-scoped (a TW filter expression selects the working set), and LLM-friendly output (CompoundTiddlers blocks for reads, before/after hashline diffs for writes).

For tutorials, see the [[Bulk Docs]] series.

!! `get_tiddlers` (Batch Read)

Fetch several tiddlers' contents in one MCP call. Use it when you already have a list of titles (from `run_filter`, `list_tiddlers`, or any prior context) and want their content together.

!!! Parameters

|! Param |! Default |! Meaning |
|`titles` |required |array of tiddler titles to fetch; input order preserved |
|`detailed` |`true` |include the text field. Ignored for plugin tiddlers (always fields-only). |
|`verbose` |`false` |include bookkeeping fields (`created`/`modified`/`creator`/`modifier`/`revision`); default drops them |
|`format` |`hashline` |`hashline` (text with line anchors), `tid` (plain text), `json` (parseable document) |
|`max_tiddlers` |`50` |hard cap on tiddler count |
|`max_bytes` |`50000` |hard cap on total output size; first-to-hit wins |

!!! Output (text formats)

CompoundTiddlers stream (`text/vnd.tiddlywiki-multiple`): each block is a `.tid` with `title:` first, other fields alphabetical, then blank line and text (when `detailed`). Blocks separated by `\n+\n`:

```
title: Best Practices
tags: Server

1#XK: !! Best Practices for Working with AI via MCP
...
+
title: Inspect Tools
tags: Server

1#MN: !! MCP Inspect Tools (Reference)
...
```

Trailers:
* `Missing: a, b, c` line: titles the wiki couldn't find.
* `(N entries truncated; raise max_tiddlers or max_bytes)`: caps hit.

!!! Output (JSON)

Unified document: `{tiddlers: [{...}], missing?: [...], truncated?: N}`. Parseable with a single `JSON.parse`.

!! `replace_in_tiddlers` (Bulk Find+Replace)

Apply one or more find+replace rules across many tiddlers in one MCP call. Default is dry-run (no writes). Use it for cross-reference renames, tag renames, regex cleanups.

!!! Parameters

|! Param |! Default |! Meaning |
|`rules` |required |array of `{pattern, replacement, regexp?, case_sensitive?, words?}` objects |
|`filter` |`[all[tiddlers]!is[system]]` |TW filter scope. Pass your own to widen or narrow. |
|`include_system` |`false` |convenience flag for `$:/` tiddlers; ignored if `filter` is set |
|`fields` |`['text','caption','list','tags']` |which fields to scan and rewrite |
|`dry_run` |`true` |preview only; nothing written. Set false to apply. |
|`max_tiddlers` |`100` |cap on modified tiddlers |
|`max_replacements_total` |`1000` |cap on total replacements |

!!! Rule object

|! Field |! Default |! Meaning |
|`pattern` |required |find pattern (literal by default; regex when `regexp=true`) |
|`replacement` |required |replacement string. Supports JS backrefs `$1..$9`, `$&`, `$$` when `regexp=true`. |
|`regexp` |`false` |treat pattern as regex |
|`case_sensitive` |`false` |case-sensitive match (default is case-insensitive) |
|`words` |`false` |wrap pattern with `\b` word boundaries |

Rules within a line are applied sequentially: rule 2 sees rule 1's output. Regex patterns get the `g` flag automatically so multiple matches per line are all replaced.

!!! Output (dry-run)

Grouped by title; before/after pairs with hashline anchors (text field) or `field:L<n>` (other fields):

```
ProjectIndex
  - 5#KP: See [[OldName]] for the spec.
  + 5#KP: See [[NewName]] for the spec.

DRY RUN: 1 replacements across 1 tiddlers
Call again with dry_run=false to apply.
```

!!! Output (apply)

Compact summary:

```
2 tiddlers modified, 3 replacements
```

Failures per tiddler are listed below the summary if any persist fails.

!!! Array fields (tags, list)

Both `tags` and `list` are arrays at runtime but strings in the `.tid` file. `replace_in_tiddlers` serialises them via `$tw.utils.stringifyList()` for matching (multi-word entries wrap in `[[...]]`) and parses the result back via `$tw.utils.parseStringArray()` on write. See [[Update tags in bulk]] for a worked example.

